        "_account_id": 131,
        "name": "Jian Yu",
        "email": "yujian@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "yujian"
      },
      "date": "2012-12-13 11:40:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nHi James,\nCould you please also fix sanity test_33c() to use get_obdfilter_param? Thanks.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "b6df02a6267569df541456168568ea9521dd9419",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2012-12-13 19:47:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nAre you sure about sanity 33c? The reason I ask is that both obdfilter and osd-ldiskfs have a stats proc entry. For my file system I noticed osd-ldiskfs stats is empty but I don't know if that is always the case.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "40f353722c930698f5b073d7647e725329bd5847",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 131,
        "name": "Jian Yu",
        "email": "yujian@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "yujian"
      },
      "date": "2012-12-14 04:47:24.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nHi Li Wei,\r\nCould you please help answer James' question above? Thanks a lot.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "6925910ec0a9f82cc072791e9d246ecb25a9fb58",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 141,
        "name": "Li Wei",
        "email": "wei.g.li@intel.com",
        "username": "liwei",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-12-14 08:31:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nJames,\n\nThank you for the patch.  In retrospect, I think the get_obdfilter_param name might be a bit misleading, though its comment is mostly correct.  I believe this led to the issue I pointed out in-line.\n\nAbout sanity 33c, you are right that \"write_bytes\" exists under obdfilter, not osd-*.  It turns out get_obdfilter_param() should only be used to get osd-specific \"stats\" entries.  We need to work out which and fix the function comment.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "45c0208be6ab3a098ae725f6c1d476ce7a35b63c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2012-12-17 12:50:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nPerhaps we should rename the function to make it clear what the purpose is?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "f849ccbe791414a3c632d2f141c9502299e9d71d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 141,
        "name": "Li Wei",
        "email": "wei.g.li@intel.com",
        "username": "liwei",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-12-17 12:57:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nJames, no objection.\n\nYu Jian, do we require 2.4 clients to be interoperable with older servers?  If there's no intention to conduct that testing, then probably {get,set}_obdfilter_param() could be retired?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "07564ca705b73d3439c33ee6a6757676d4604e86",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 131,
        "name": "Jian Yu",
        "email": "yujian@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "yujian"
      },
      "date": "2012-12-20 09:49:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n> Yu Jian, do we require 2.4 clients to be interoperable with older servers?\r\n\r\nThe answer is yes. E.g.,\r\n\r\nhttps://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/bcd4653e-4a83-11e2-8a7b-52540035b04c",
